5–Overleden","1277–Female":"1277–Overleden","1300–Male":"1300–Overleden","1250–1297":"1250–1297","1260–Female":"1260–Overleden","about 1280":"circa 1280","1300":"1300","1277":"1277","1297":"1297","1275":"1275","1285":"1285","about 1300":"circa 1300","1250":"1250","about 1275":"circa 1275","1260":"1260","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Schotland"},"en":{"about 1275–":"about 1275–Deceased","1275–Male":"1275–Deceased","1277–Female":"1277–Deceased","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","1250–1297":"1250–1297","1260–Female":"1260–Deceased","about 1280":"about 1280","1300":"1300","1277":"1277","1297":"1297","1275":"1275","1285":"1285","about 1300":"about 1300","1250":"1250","about 1275":"about 1275","1260":"1260","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thompson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>T(h)om(me)</i> (see   Thom  ) + <i>-son</i> ‘son of <i>Tom</i>’.   Thomson   is usually the Scottish form, that with the intrusive <i>-p-</i> being English. Both forms are common in Ireland. The surname <i>Thompson</i> is also very common among African Americans.","Americanized form of Danish, Norwegian, and North German   Thomsen   and of its Swedish cognate <b>Thomsson</b>. Compare   Thomson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Thomson","meanings":["Scottish, English and northern Irish: variant of   Thompson  .","Scottish: sometimes an Anglicized form of Gaelic <i>McThomas</i>; see   McTavish  ,   McComish  .","Americanized form of Danish, Norwegian, and North German   Thomsen  . Compare   Thompson  ."]},{"name":"Thom","meanings":["Scottish and English: from the Middle English personal name <i>T(h)om(me)</i>, a pet form of   Thomas  . In Scotland, <i>Thom</i> is also an Anglicized form of Gaelic <i>Mac Thom</i>, see   McComb  .","German: from the personal name <i>Thom</i>, a pet form of   Thomas  . This surname is also found in France.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 譚, see   Tan   1."]},{"name":"Tomson","meanings":["English: variant of   Thompson  ."]},{"name":"Thompsom","meanings":["Altered form of   Thompson  ."]},{"name":"Tompson","meanings":["English: variant of   Thompson  ."]}]},{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When James Thompson was born about 1275, in Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, his father, Sir Thomas Thompson III, was 27 and his mother, Mrs Thomas Thompson III, was 16. He married Isobel Davidson about 1300, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in Scotland, and was buried in Scotland."},"et":{"about 1275–":"umbes 1275–Surnud","1275–Male":"1275–Surnud","1277–Female":"1277–Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1250–1297":"1250–1297","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","about 1280":"umbes 1280","1300":"1300","1277":"1277","1297":"1297","1275":"1275","1285":"1285","about 1300":"umbes 1300","1250":"1250","about 1275":"umbes 1275","1260":"1260","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1275–":"noin 1275–Kuollut","1275–Male":"1275–Kuollut","1277–Female":"1277–Kuollut","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1250–1297":"1250–1297","1260–Female":"1260–Kuollut","about 1280":"noin 1280","1300":"1300","1277":"1277","1297":"1297","1275":"1275","1285":"1285","about 1300":"noin 1300","1250":"1250","about 1275":"noin 1275","1260":"1260","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"about 1275–":"environ 1275–Décédé","1275–Male":"1275–Décédé","1277–Female":"1277–Décédée","1300–Male":"1300–Décédé","1250–1297":"1250–1297","1260–Female":"1260–Décédée","about 1280":"environ 1280","1300":"1300","1277":"1277","1297":"1297","1275":"1275","1285":"1285","about 1300":"environ 1300","1250":"1250","about 1275":"environ 1275","1260":"1260","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Écosse","Scotland":"Écosse","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Écosse","lifeSummary":"Lorsque James Thompson est né environ 1275, à Perth, Perthshire, Écosse, son père, Sir Thomas Thompson III, avait 27 ans et sa mère, Mrs Thomas Thompson III, avait 16 ans. Il